# LLK / Compute Kernel Code Conciseness

Generated code in this repo (kernels, LLK API layers, compute API headers, LLK tests) MUST be terse. Reviewers consistently flag the same anti-patterns. Avoid them upfront.

## 1. Do NOT duplicate code across `if` / `if constexpr` / `#if` branches

If two branches call the SAME function and differ only in a value being passed (especially a `constexpr` value being passed as a template / non-type-template argument), drop the branch entirely and forward the value into the call. The compiler will instantiate the right specialization.

```cpp
// BAD — branches differ only in the template argument
if constexpr (flag_en) {
    _llk_foo_<true>(...);
} else {
    _llk_foo_<false>(...);
}

// GOOD — forward the value directly; no branch, no duplication
_llk_foo_<flag_en>(...);
```

The same applies when the only difference is a runtime argument, a constant, a single function name selected by a `constexpr` predicate, etc. — extract the differing piece, do not re-emit the surrounding call.

Also hoist loop-invariant and branch-invariant lookups (e.g. `g_dfb_interface[operand_id]`, `tc_slots[tc_idx].rd_entry_idx`, `get_operand_*`) OUT of per-tile loops and out of `if`/`else`/`#if` arms when both arms compute the same value.

## 2. Extend the existing function — do NOT add a parallel near-duplicate

If you need a variant of an existing LLK / metal API function with one or two more arguments or template parameters, modify the existing function (add a default-valued parameter or template parameter so existing call sites keep compiling). Do NOT leave a second function with the smaller signature alongside it.

```cpp
// BAD — parallel functions, near-identical bodies
inline void llk_foo_(uint32_t dst_index);

template <DataCopyType type = DataCopyType::A2D>
inline void llk_foo_(uint32_t dst_index, uint32_t operand = 0);

// GOOD — single function; defaults preserve old call sites
template <DataCopyType type = DataCopyType::A2D>
inline void llk_foo_(uint32_t dst_index, uint32_t operand = 0);
```

Do NOT add unused/dummy template parameters "for symmetry" with another arch (WH/BH↔Quasar) — only carry parameters the function actually uses. If a parameter is genuinely required only for arch parity, mark it `[[maybe_unused]]` and document it.

## 3. Search tt-llk before writing a new helper

Before introducing a helper at the metal/ckernels layer, search the tt-llk tree for one that already exists or can be lightly extended:

- `tt_llk_wormhole_b0/{llk_lib,common/inc}/`
- `tt_llk_blackhole/{llk_lib,common/inc}/`
- `tt_llk_quasar/{llk_lib,common/inc}/`

Also check the matching layers in tt-metal (paths relative to repo root):
- `tt_metal/hw/ckernels/{wormhole_b0,blackhole,quasar}/metal/llk_api/`
- `tt_metal/hw/inc/api/compute/`

Use Grep / Glob (or the appropriate sage subagent — `sage-wormhole`, `sage-blackhole`, `sage-quasar`) to confirm. If a similar helper exists under a different name (e.g. `is_32bit_format` vs a new `quasar_unary_bcast_unpack_to_dest_enabled`), reuse / rename it instead of adding a parallel one. Do not expose a new public API method when the work belongs in an existing one (or in a `static` / unnamed-namespace local helper in the same file).

## 4. Audit every template / compile-time arg on touched functions

For every function you add or modify, audit each template parameter and `constexpr` argument:

- If the parameter is **never read** in the body, mark the corresponding usage `[[maybe_unused]]` (or drop the parameter entirely if no caller depends on it for overload selection / arch parity).
- If the parameter IS used, but the implementation only handles a subset of its valid values, add a `static_assert` that pins down the supported permutations. Untested / unimplemented permutations must fail at compile time, not silently miscompile or fall through.

```cpp
// BAD — only ROW / COL are actually implemented, but NONE / SCALAR compile and silently do the wrong thing
template <BroadcastType BCAST>
inline void _llk_foo_() {
    // implementation only correct for ROW and COL
}

// GOOD — illegal permutations are rejected at compile time
template <BroadcastType BCAST>
inline void _llk_foo_() {
    static_assert(BCAST == BroadcastType::ROW || BCAST == BroadcastType::COL,
                  "_llk_foo_ only supports BroadcastType::ROW / COL");
    // implementation
}
```

Apply the same pattern to bool / enum template params with limited support, to `is_fp32_dest_acc_en`-style flags that aren't wired through every code path, and to `APPROXIMATE` / `ITERATIONS` / similar params that are accepted but not actually exercised.

## Reviewer checklist (apply BEFORE finishing the edit)

- [ ] No `if` / `if constexpr` / `#if` arm duplicates code that the other arm also runs.
- [ ] Loop-invariant and branch-invariant computations are hoisted (compute once, reuse).
- [ ] No two functions in the touched file (or its arch siblings) differ only by added parameters / template args — the older one is removed and call sites use defaults.
- [ ] No new helper that an existing tt-llk / `llk_api` / compute-API function already provides; reused where possible.
- [ ] Every template / compile-time arg on touched functions is either used, marked `[[maybe_unused]]`, or constrained by a `static_assert` that pins down the supported permutations.
- [ ] No unused template parameters added solely to mirror another architecture's signature.
